Wild Animal Classification

Introduction:

In this blog post we will take a look at the implementation of Wild Animal Classification using various models. This blog post will also introduce some of the basic concepts of these algorithms. This blog post will be beginner friendly and easy to understand.


Dataset:

In this task will be using Wild Animal Images (https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/whenamancodes/wild-animals-images) dataset provided by Aman Chauhan on kaggle website. It consists of collection of images of various wild animals such as Cheetah, Fox, Tiger, Lion, etc. Images are segregated into directories as per the name of the animal itself. The dataset provided consists of same images in various sizes such as 224, 300, 512. But in this tutorial we will be 512 sized images.

1. ResNet50 Model:

CNN is a sequence of layers, and every layer of a CNN transforms one volume of activation to another through a differentiable function. Generally three main types of layers are used to build ConvNet architectures: Convolutional Layer, Pooling Layer, and Fully-Connected Layer.


Convolutional Layer:


The first layer of a Convolutional Neural Network is always a Convolutional Layer. Convolutional layers apply a convolution operation to the input, passing the result to the next layer. A convolution converts all the pixels in its receptive field into a single value. This layer will detect various features in the images. It gives an output in the form of vector.


Source: https://cs231n.github.io/convolutional-networks/#pool


Pooling Layer :


Pooling layer will reduce the dimensions of the output of its previous layer. Pooling involves selecting a pooling operation, much like a filter to be applied to feature maps. The size of the pooling operation or filter is smaller than the size of the feature map; specifically, it is almost always 22 pixels applied with a stride of 2 pixels. There are various types of pooling operations such as average pooling and max pooling.


Fully Connected Layer:


Fully-connected layers, connect every input neuron to every output neuron. Fully connected layers are generally used as last layers of the CNN. These layers will help to convert extracted features from previous layers into final output class.

ResNet50 is the pre-trained CNN model. It consists of different 50 layers of convolution and max-pool as shown in following diagram.


Source: https://towardsdatascience.com/the-annotated-resnet-50-a6c536034758


Here we have initialized a ResNet50 model.

This model will have 50 conv layers already present, we just need to add fully connected dense layer. For the dense layer we will use ReLu activation function.

2. kNN :


The k-nearest neighbors (KNN) algorithm is a simple, easy-to-implement supervised machine learning algorithm that can be used to solve both classification and regression problems. KNN assumes that similar things will appear near to each other.

Source: https://www.analyticssteps.com/blogs/how-does-k-nearest-neighbor-works-machine-learning-classification-problem

KNN works by calculating the distance of the datapoint with other datapoints in dataset and based in the maximum number of nearest datapoints, it will do the classification.

Pros of KNN:

1. Simple algorithms

2. High accuracy

Cons of KNN:

1. Slow prediction rate

2. Requires high storage

Here we have used KNN model from scikit-learn library. Here we have used k=10 value. That means the algorithms will select top 10 neighbors for predicting the class of datapoints.


3. SVM :


Support Vector Machine is another supervised machine learning model. SVM can generalize between two different classes if the set of labelled data is provided in the training set to the algorithm. The main function of the SVM is to check for that hyperplane that is able to distinguish between the two classes.

The algorithms will find the best hyperplane that will effectively separate the different datapoints in dataset. It will find the optimal plane such that the distance between the support vectors (nearest datapoints to the plane) of all the class is maximum from the plane. And this distance is called as margin. This algorithm will try to maximize this margin.


Source: https://www.analyticssteps.com/blogs/how-does-support-vector-machine-algorithm-works-machine-learning
